========================================================
 Baseliner INSTALL guide
========================================================

perl -Mlocal::lib=$PERL_LOCAL_LIB -MCPAN -e shell

Bundle::CPAN
YAML::XS
Path::Class

========================================================
 Setting up Environment variables
========================================================

Put the following in your .profile or .bashrc file:

Unix:

export BASELINER_HOME=/path/to/baseliner
export BASELINER_ENV=<conf_file_suffix>
export PATH=$BASELINER_HOME/bin:$PATH

Windows:

set BASELINER_HOME=drive:\path\to\baseliner
set BASELINER_ENV=<conf_file_suffix>
set PATH=$BASELINER_HOME\bin;%PATH%

========================================================
 Upgrading the Database
========================================================

Use the following Baseliner utility to upgrade the 
database after updating the Baseliner version:

bali deploy --env '<conf_suffix>' --diff

Nothing will run until you tell it to do so. 

========================================================
 Checking for installed dependencies
========================================================

Use the following Baseliner utility:

bali perldeps --check

That reports uninstalled Perl packages found in Baseliner.

========================================================
 AIX
========================================================

## Manual Install

cpanm -n DBI DBD::Oracle
cpanm -n Catalyst::Engine::CGI
cpanm -n Catalyst::Engine::HTTP::Prefork

## HTTP::HeaderParser::XS

It comes configured with the g++ compiler by default,
which, in case you're using the IBM VAC suite compilers, 
may not be available. 

Try this:

cpanm --look HTTP::HeaderParser::XS
make CC="xlc_r -+" LD=xlc_r

## DBD::Oracle

To avoid OCIPing problem, which is missing from
the 10.2 Oracle client in AIX machines, you may 
need to set the client as 10.0. 

cpanm --look DBD::Oracle
perl Makefile.PL -V 10.0  

You may also need this:

cpanm -n Math::Base36
cpanm -n DateTime::Format::Oracle
